<h1 id="what-is-a-linear-function">What is a Linear Function</h1>

<p>A Linear function is one which <strong>applies a scalar multiple to each individual variable within the function</strong> and **passes through the origin at $x=0$ **.</p>

\[f(x_1,x_2,\dots,x_n) = \alpha_1 x_1 + \alpha_2 x_2 + \dots + \alpha_n x_n\]

<p>As a result, the following are not linear functions</p>

<ol>
  <li>$f(x,y) = xy$</li>
  <li>$f(x,y) =sin(x)$</li>
  <li>$f(x) = x^n$</li>
  <li>$f(x) = 2x+3$</li>
</ol>

<p>We observe that</p>

<p>(1) is not a linear function because individual variables are multiplied against one another rather than using a scalar multiple (e. 2,3,4)</p>

<p>(2) is not a linear function because a non-linear function is applied against a variable</p>

<p>(3) is not a linear function because a variable is raised to a power $n$ which is not equal to $1$</p>

<p>(4) is not a linear function because it does not pass through the origin at $x=0$. It is instead a [[affine function]]</p>

